TRIP COMMENTS: What a wonderful thing it was to do most of the tour in darkness! We had great views of the two Barn Owls, wonderful overlapping sounds from the GHOwls. Also enjoyed mammals - Striped Skunk, Raccoon, Jackrabbits everywhere, Deer.  Watched as a Jackrabbit approached, then ran away from the Skunk.  Soon after the skunk disappeared, the Jackrabbit returned and used his nose to retrace the Skunk''s path.  Me and Peggy

We first spotted this bird perched high in a tree about 400 meters north of the viewing platform.  As we approached in our vehicle looking for a photo opportunity, the bird left its perch and swooped on the ducks in the nearest pond.  It's action caused thousands of ducks and geese to rise into the air in a great commotion that allowed us to experience a sense of wonder and enjoyment.  Truly one of those memorable moments in the field.

The purpose of this visit was to witness the Yellow Rail observed here over the past 3 weeks. No observations had been published this week so Ken Burton and I were not certain the bird was still being heard. I didn''t see Jeff Seay''s 7/17/10 post until I returned.  We walked the trail to the noted location, about 200 meters beyond the north edge of open water to a point where a couple of crossed sticks were located next to the trail. We arrived at the X about 1630 hrs and immediately heard the nearby bird, about 20 meters away, estimated by triangulation of the sound.  We spent 10 minutes here then walked toward the north end of the meadow into Lassen NP then returned to the crossed sticks.  Ken first heard the 2nd bird, much further into the marsh, at least 70 meters away from the first and maybe a little south from perpendicular to the first bird.  Because the near bird was so close, it was difficult to hear the more distant bird until the nearer bird stopped calling.  We both heard both birds calling alternately and together. Definitely 2 birds.

SPECIES COMMENTS: adult, When I first arrived I heard an obviously large bird flying past over head and looked up to see it was the eagle carrying prey.  I jumped back in the car and attempted to follow it up Cottontail Creek canyon.  It stayed of the east side of the canyon and gained altitude.  When I got to the first broad canyon that headed off to the east (near the old Storni Ranch)I could not find the bird.  I drove back down to Whale Rock Res and saw presumable the same bird returning to the reservoir without prey.  Certainly suggests it was carrying food to young; nesting has been suspected here for a few years.

SPECIES COMMENTS: This immature Bald Eagle appeared to be a bird just entering its second calendar year in very worn juvenal plumage and molting into first basic plumage. It had much more white on the tail than I usually see on the tail of a young Bald Eagle. There were irregular pale areas, but no true white, anywhere on the body except for the tail, which appeared entirely white except for an narrow, irregular dark terminal band that broadened at the corners. Its body structure, size, bill, and overall appearance were perfectly normal for a Bald Eagle, but the extent of white on the tail of a young bird surprised me.

Chipping Sparrows are apparently breeding in this area and DE Junco have been confirmed here as breeding. Third time Bald Eagle has flown over this area (probably from Berryessa). A Cassin''s Vireo was singing here two weeks ago, that was a surprise, but two singing today was startling. Mike Rippey reports they have bred nearby in riparian habitat in Solano County so I must presume these birds are on territory here. Hairy WP was also a big surprise, as they have NOT been here before this spring.
flock of Cackling Geese overhead flying west to east toward Rumsey.  Bizarre.
